  <h2>I Run Both. Here's What I Actually Think.</h2>

  <p>
    I have Bambu Lab machines and Prusa machines in my shop. I use both for production work, prototyping, and client orders. I'm not loyal to either brand — I'm loyal to getting parts out the door. So here's an honest take that I don't see enough people giving.
  </p>

  <h2>Speed: Bambu Wins, But It's Not the Whole Story</h2>

  <p>
    Bambu Lab printers are fast. The X1C and P1S print at speeds that make a stock Prusa MK4 look like it's going backwards. If all you care about is throughput — parts per hour — Bambu wins by a wide margin. The AMS (automatic material system) makes multi-color and multi-material work seamless. The LiDAR first-layer inspection catches failures early. The ecosystem is polished.
  </p>

  <p>
    But speed isn't free. Bambu achieves its speed through tight hardware-software integration and proprietary firmware. You run their slicer, their firmware, their cloud. When it works — which is most of the time — it's brilliant. When it doesn't, you're waiting for a firmware update from a company in Shenzhen.
  </p>

  <h2>Openness: Prusa's Real Advantage</h2>

  <p>
    Prusa machines are open source. The firmware is on GitHub. The slicer (PrusaSlicer) is open source and works with every printer on the market. You can modify, repair, and upgrade a Prusa with parts you source yourself. The bill of materials is public. Community mods are endless.
  </p>

  <p>
    This matters more than most people realize. When a stepper motor fails on my Prusa at 10 PM, I can pull a replacement from my parts drawer and have it running by midnight. When something fails on a Bambu, I'm often ordering a proprietary module and waiting for shipping. In a production environment, downtime costs money.
  </p>

  <p>
    Prusa's CORE One changed the equation significantly — it's enclosed, it's faster than the old MK4, and it keeps the open-source DNA. It's not Bambu-fast, but it's fast enough for most production work, and I can fix it myself.
  </p>

  <h2>Print Quality: It's Closer Than You Think</h2>

  <p>
    Out of the box, Bambu printers produce excellent prints with minimal tuning. The automatic calibration handles most of it. Prusa requires more initial setup but once dialed in, the quality is comparable. I've done side-by-side prints of the same part on both and the differences are cosmetic at best.
  </p>

  <p>
    Where Bambu pulls ahead is consistency across machines. If you have five X1Cs, they'll all produce nearly identical parts. Prusa machines have more unit-to-unit variation, especially the older i3 models. The CORE One tightens this up considerably.
  </p>

  <h2>The Proprietary Problem</h2>

  <p>
    Here's the thing nobody wants to talk about: Bambu Lab can change the rules whenever they want. They've already tried restricting third-party firmware. They've pushed cloud requirements. They control the slicer, the firmware, and increasingly the material profiles.
  </p>

  <p>
    Today, the Bambu ecosystem is open enough to be usable. But the trend line points toward more control, not less. If you're building a business on Bambu hardware, you're building on rented ground. One firmware update can change what your machine does and how it does it.
  </p>

  <p>
    Prusa can't do that. The hardware is yours, the firmware is yours, and the community ensures it stays that way. For a production shop, that's not ideology — it's risk management.
  </p>

  <h2>What I Actually Recommend</h2>

  <p>
    For hobbyists and people who want to print and not tinker: Bambu. The A1 or P1S are exceptional machines for the price. Plug in, load filament, print. The experience is Apple-like and for a lot of people, that's exactly right.
  </p>

  <p>
    For production shops, makerspaces, and anyone building a business on 3D printing: Prusa. The CORE One is the machine to buy. The repairability, the open firmware, and the PrusaSlicer ecosystem make it a safer long-term investment. When your livelihood depends on your machines, you need to own them completely — not just the hardware, but the software stack too.
  </p>

  <p>
    For my own shop, I run both. Bambu machines handle high-throughput commodity prints. Prusa machines handle engineering materials, experimental work, and anything where I need full control of the process. It's not about which brand is better — it's about matching the tool to the job.
  </p>

  <h2>The Real Conversation</h2>

  <p>
    The community treats this like a sports rivalry. Bambu fans trash Prusa for being slow. Prusa fans trash Bambu for being proprietary. Both sides are right and both sides are missing the point.
  </p>

  <p>
    The question isn't which printer is better. The question is what happens to 3D printing as an industry if the dominant player controls the entire stack from hardware to cloud. That's the conversation worth having, and almost nobody is having it honestly.
  </p>
